TY  - JOUR
T1  - Gold Monetization and Gold Discipline
AU  - Flood, Robert P.
AU  - Garber, Peter M.
Y1  - 1984/02/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261209
DO  - 10.1086/261209
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 90
EP  - 107
VL  - 92
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The substantial U.S. inflations of the 1970s led to some popular support for commodity-based money. Gold has had a special role in historical commodity-money schemes, and it emerged as a leading contender in recent discussions. In October 1980 Congress established the Gold Commission to study the possible remonetization of gold. In this paper we analyze some gold monetization schemes proposed to the commission. We find that the adoption of these proposals need not lead to the price-level stability their proponents seek. Even a well-designed commodity-money scheme is a foolproof inflation guard only when the scheme's permanence is guaranteed. Permanence may possibly be guaranteed by an underlying political economy that abhors inflation, but merely the enactment of a new ephemeral rule does not ensure permanence.
AB  - The substantial U.S. inflations of the 1970s led to some popular support for commodity-based money. Gold has had a special role in historical commodity-money schemes, and it emerged as a leading contender in recent discussions. In October 1980 Congress established the Gold Commission to study the possible remonetization of gold. In this paper we analyze some gold monetization schemes proposed to the commission. We find that the adoption of these proposals need not lead to the price-level stability their proponents seek. Even a well-designed commodity-money scheme is a foolproof inflation guard only when the scheme's permanence is guaranteed. Permanence may possibly be guaranteed by an underlying political economy that abhors inflation, but merely the enactment of a new ephemeral rule does not ensure permanence.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261209
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261209
Y2  - 2024/03/23
ER  - 

